<p><a href="/wiki/Major_General" title="Major General" class="mw-redirect">Major General</a> <b>Sir Charles John Melliss</b> <a href="/wiki/Victoria_Cross" title="Victoria Cross">VC</a>, <a href="/wiki/Knight_Commander_of_the_Order_of_the_Bath" title="Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath" class="mw-redirect">KCB</a>, <a href="/wiki/Knight_Commander_of_Order_of_St_Michael_and_St_George" title="Knight Commander of Order of St Michael and St George" class="mw-redirect">KCMG</a> (12 September 1862 – 6 June 1936) was a British military officer of the late 19th and early 20th centuries. Melliss was a recipient of the <a href="/wiki/Victoria_Cross" title="Victoria Cross">Victoria Cross</a>, the highest and most prestigious award for gallantry in the face of the enemy that can be awarded to <a href="/wiki/United_Kingdom" title="United Kingdom">British</a> and <a href="/wiki/Commonwealth_of_Nations" title="Commonwealth of Nations">Commonwealth</a> forces. A staff officer in the <a href="/wiki/Mesopotamian_Campaign" title="Mesopotamian Campaign" class="mw-redirect">Mesopotamian Campaign</a> of <a href="/wiki/World_War_I" title="World War I">World War I</a>, he was captured after the <a href="/wiki/Siege_of_Kut" title="Siege of Kut">Siege of Kut</a>.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
<div id="toctitle">
